WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.400
So happy Thursday, everybody. Welcome to the Data Science Hangout. Hope everyone's having

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:21.200
a great week. If we haven't met before, I'm Rachel Dempsey. I lead our pro community at

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:28.000
Posit. If this is your first time ever joining us at a Data Science Hangout, welcome. This

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.279
is our open space to chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing, and getting

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:38.720
to hear about what's going on in the world of data across many different industries and

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:46.200
companies. And so we're here every Thursday, except for July. At the same time, same place.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:51.119
So if you're watching this recording on YouTube later, you can also add these events to your

00:00:51.119 --> 00:00:56.660
own calendar using the link below. But together, we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:01.299
environment for everyone. So we'd love to hear from everybody, no matter your level

00:01:01.299 --> 00:01:08.900
of experience, the area of work, or industry. It is also totally okay to just listen in

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:14.860
and just hang out here with us. There's also three ways you can jump in and either ask

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:19.699
questions or provide your own perspective on certain topics too. So you can always jump

00:01:19.699 --> 00:01:24.620
in by raising your hand on Zoom and I'll keep an eye out. You can put questions in the Zoom

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:29.459
chat. And feel free to just put a little star next to it if you want me to read it

00:01:29.459 --> 00:01:34.980
out loud instead, if you're maybe in a busy coffee shop or something. And then third,

00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:39.699
we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously. And I think Hannah

00:01:39.699 --> 00:01:46.860
or Curtis will share that in the chat here in just a second. But I am so excited to have

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:54.300
my colleague, Joe Chang, joining us here today as our featured leader. Joe is the CTO and

00:01:54.300 --> 00:02:01.699
first employee at Posit, well back then RStudio, where he helped create the RStudio IDE and

00:02:01.699 --> 00:02:09.220
Shiny web framework along with countless complimentary tools and packages. And Joe, I'd love to get

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:13.339
things kicked off here by having you also introduce yourself and just kind of share

00:02:13.339 --> 00:02:18.419
a little bit about your role and what it means to be CTO at Posit.

00:02:19.139 --> 00:02:27.100
Yeah, thanks for having me. CTO is actually an honorary title. There are a lot of different

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:35.259
kinds of CTOs in the industry. And one of them is basically an engineer that joined

00:02:35.259 --> 00:02:40.580
very early and it's an honorary title. And that's what it certainly it started out as

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:48.419
for me. Started out as purely an acknowledgement that there are strategic conversations that

00:02:48.419 --> 00:02:55.220
the board and the executive team would like me to be part of. But my day-to-day was still

00:02:55.220 --> 00:03:02.139
100% software engineer and then team lead. And these days, I think probably 90 plus percent

00:03:02.139 --> 00:03:11.619
of my time is as a team lead on a Shiny team. It's a team of about 11. And I, you know,

00:03:11.619 --> 00:03:17.899
every once in a while will do more CTO stuff, which is having conversations that are more

00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:22.899
sort of at the strategic level with the other execs to talk about the direction that we're

00:03:22.899 --> 00:03:33.779
taking the company in. So for my day-to-day, I try to do, you know, 50% coding and 50%

00:03:33.779 --> 00:03:40.820
leading the team. That usually is more like 15% coding and 85% leading the team. There's

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:45.940
always emergencies and, you know, last-minute conversations that come up. So I do a lot

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:54.179
of code reviews. I do a ton of sort of helping to decide feature directions. I do some talking

00:03:54.179 --> 00:04:00.820
with customers. I do some support. Just really anything that comes up. And we try to run

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:07.860
our team that way for the most part. Most of our roles are relatively loose and flexible.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:14.500
So we really value having everyone on the team, or certainly all the software engineers,

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:18.739
to be really thoughtful about what kind of features would be interesting to add to Shiny

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:23.579
to be able to design their own features to implement and to be responsible for the quality

00:04:23.579 --> 00:04:30.220
and support of their own features. So yes, for me, it's Shiny all the time. Shiny day

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:39.660
and night. Shiny for R. Shiny for Python. Packages that complement Shiny. HTML widgets.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:45.660
For the last month, I've been working on a sort of the equivalent to the DT package

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:51.220
for R, which is a way to view data tables, data frames, and data tables very quickly

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:56.420
with a rich HTML interface. I've been working on that for Shiny for Python, where we have

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:01.859
not had that capability in the past. So that's one particular feature that I've been working

00:05:01.859 --> 00:05:07.940
on. But yeah, for sure, most of my time is in meetings and helping other team members

00:05:08.019 --> 00:05:14.339
achieve what they need to. Thanks, Joe. And I forgot to ask you this, but I usually ask

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:20.179
everybody, what's something that you like to do outside of work too? For me, that's cycling.

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:27.700
I don't do it nearly as much as I'd like to, but that's my favorite way to blow off some steam

00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:36.899
after a long day. Thank you. Okay, so while we're waiting for some questions to come in from

00:05:36.899 --> 00:05:42.899
everybody here, thank you so much for the intro. And I'm wondering, if somebody had never heard

00:05:42.899 --> 00:05:52.100
about Shiny before, how would you describe it? Yeah. So to me, Shiny is fundamentally about

00:05:52.100 --> 00:06:01.619
letting data scientists create interactive web applications to take their analysis that they're

00:06:02.339 --> 00:06:07.140
already doing on their own machine and taking the insights that they are gaining from their data on

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:12.899
their own machine and being able to expose that to usually other people, sometimes to themselves,

00:06:12.899 --> 00:06:18.019
but usually to expose that to other people in a really dynamic and interactive way.

00:06:19.619 --> 00:06:28.660
In the past before Shiny, I think you would see, I mean, it's still very common to issue a static

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:33.459
report and send it to someone. And if there were lots of variables in your analysis, if there were

00:06:33.459 --> 00:06:38.339
lots of different ways you might want to slice and dice the data, you would either just add more and

00:06:38.339 --> 00:06:46.179
more pages to that PDF or HTML page. And we had a lot of people tell us that they would exchange

00:06:46.179 --> 00:06:51.220
PDFs with thousands of pages and good luck trying to find the page that you want. Or you would do

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:55.380
this back and forth of like, okay, here's my best guess at what you want. And then you'd have this

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:59.299
endless email back and forth of, how about this? How about this? How about this? Until they find the

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:06.019
needle in the haystack that they're looking for. So that's just one example of when it might be

00:07:06.019 --> 00:07:12.100
useful to take insights that you can easily gain for yourself on your own console and your own

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:17.299
notebook, and to be able to turn that into something that empowers other people in your

00:07:17.299 --> 00:07:21.779
organization or that you're collaborating with, or just that you think might find your data

00:07:21.779 --> 00:07:26.579
interesting, to be able to interact with that data in a more dynamic and modern way.

00:07:27.940 --> 00:07:34.579
That's how it started, that and teaching statistics. That was the other big thing that we

00:07:34.579 --> 00:07:42.100
were sort of very focused on in the beginning. And boy, it's been interesting what people have taken

00:07:43.059 --> 00:07:52.660
Shiny and used it for. So in terms of what it's for, everything from BI to machine learning and

00:07:52.660 --> 00:08:01.059
large language models and games and fantasy football draft analyzers, all sorts of interesting

00:08:01.059 --> 00:08:07.940
things people have done with it. But one of the most important things for us is that it is

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:13.700
accessible for anyone who calls themselves a data scientist. So you do need to code. That is very

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:17.859
important to us. That's one of the core tenets of our company, is that we really believe in code

00:08:17.859 --> 00:08:23.459
first. But you don't have to be able to code in web development technologies. You don't need to

00:08:23.459 --> 00:08:29.779
be a web developer to create Shiny apps. You just need to be conversant in the language of data

00:08:29.779 --> 00:08:39.299
science. Thank you. And I see an anonymous question that came in a little bit ago, which was,

00:08:39.299 --> 00:08:45.700
what's the elevator pitch? And then maybe further discussion points for investing in Shiny rather

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:51.700
than using point-and-click BI tools. Yeah, absolutely. That's a good question. And it's

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:57.299
interesting. I had one thing in mind when I created Shiny, and then that has sort of evolved as I've

00:08:57.299 --> 00:09:02.500
gotten feedback from people who have spent a lot of time using both BI tools and Shiny. So

00:09:04.739 --> 00:09:10.659
my elevator pitch in the beginning was that BI tools are great, and you should use Shiny when

00:09:10.659 --> 00:09:15.380
those run out of steam. In the beginning, that was really about advanced analytics. So if you

00:09:15.380 --> 00:09:20.739
want to just draw some scatter plots and line charts, I mean, BI tools can do a lot. I'm not

00:09:20.739 --> 00:09:26.179
trying to be glib. But if what you're trying to do is completely within the wheelhouse of BI tools,

00:09:26.179 --> 00:09:36.099
great. Like, no problem. Those are awesome tools. And if you find yourself wanting to use

00:09:36.099 --> 00:09:40.340
a predictive model that they don't support, and there are a lot that they don't support,

00:09:41.299 --> 00:09:47.859
or you want to pull from some data source that is more dynamic than a BI tool is designed for,

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:53.859
then use Shiny. So it's sort of like, for the simple stuff, sure, use a BI tool. I mean,

00:09:53.859 --> 00:09:58.900
if you can afford it, a lot of them aren't cheap. But then for the other stuff, use Shiny.

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:06.900
And I actually had a number of people tell me that it was actually not like that for them. That,

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:13.859
in fact, numerous times I've heard people have to deploy to BI tools within their organization, or

00:10:15.859 --> 00:10:22.020
if they're consultants and they're at a client, that the only deployment target they can feasibly

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:28.979
use is, say, Tableau. They would actually build it in Shiny first and then port it to Tableau.

00:10:28.979 --> 00:10:32.739
And I was like, you're going to have to explain to me why you're doing that. That is very surprising.

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:41.619
And what they said to me was that a number of the advantages of just using code in the first place

00:10:43.059 --> 00:10:46.659
were just such big advantages that they didn't want to give them up when they were using Tableau.

00:10:47.059 --> 00:10:53.140
So first of all, it was very common, they would say, for them to work really hard and come up with

00:10:53.140 --> 00:11:01.299
this very sophisticated Tableau application, or Tableau dashboard. And then the stakeholder would

00:11:01.299 --> 00:11:07.859
say, oh, that looks great. Please just change this or that thing. And this or that thing,

00:11:07.859 --> 00:11:12.099
because of the way these point and click tools work, you would have to start the whole thing

00:11:12.099 --> 00:11:15.539
over. I mean, you would have all the insights you gained along the way, but the mechanics of

00:11:15.539 --> 00:11:20.340
building it, you would have to build it again from scratch. Whereas for a Shiny app, you could

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:27.859
just replace a single line to use a different data source. Or sometimes they would be like,

00:11:27.859 --> 00:11:34.340
that's great, and we want the same dashboard now for these 10 other departments, these 10 other

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:40.500
scenarios. And again, you'd be in this position of the reuse was really a lot harder than when

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:47.780
you're dealing with code. So that was one. The second people told me was that the extensibility

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:56.659
was really frustrating for them. To build a BI dashboard that serves you well for a while, but

00:11:56.659 --> 00:12:02.659
then to know that there is always the possibility of some new requirement arriving that they would

00:12:02.659 --> 00:12:09.859
not be able to satisfy, whereas Shiny having a ceiling that's essentially, by comparison,

00:12:09.859 --> 00:12:17.539
it's infinite, was very comforting to them. And the third is that the feedback I received was

00:12:17.539 --> 00:12:23.380
that if you know how to code, that doing a Shiny dashboard in code is just more fun than the

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:27.460
point and click. Especially when you know what you want to do and you know how you would code it,

00:12:28.179 --> 00:12:33.299
it's frustrating to try to figure out how the point and click interface wants you to express that.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:42.099
And then finally, just being pragmatic, people told me that it's like a better

00:12:42.099 --> 00:12:46.500
resume builder to have built a bunch of Shiny apps than to have built a bunch of Tableau

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:51.219
point and click dashboards that it led them to better career opportunities. I'm just being

00:12:51.219 --> 00:12:56.500
real with you guys. That's not something like we put on the website, but I've

00:12:56.500 --> 00:13:01.299
heard that too many times to think that that's not a real motivation for some people.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:04.260
Shiny, because we're all control freaks, totally, Luke.

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:10.020
Joe, a few people were commenting that was a very long elevator ride.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:15.460
Yeah, I tend to do that.

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:22.419
No, that was great, though. Thank you so much. Ethan, I see you had asked a question in the

00:13:22.419 --> 00:13:27.700
Zoom chat. Do you want to jump in here? Yeah, sure. Hi, Joe. I actually haven't tried

00:13:28.659 --> 00:13:33.219
Shiny in Python yet, but just want to get you some high level thoughts when you're

00:13:33.219 --> 00:13:37.780
developing Shiny for Python. Is there anything that you've learned from developing it for R

00:13:37.780 --> 00:13:46.659
first? And in terms of feature parity, is it a asset or liability for the engineering team

00:13:46.659 --> 00:13:53.539
when developing Shiny for Python? Yeah, very good questions.

00:13:53.780 --> 00:14:03.059
I'd say one of the biggest things we learned, I'll say there's two main things that come to

00:14:03.059 --> 00:14:10.179
mind when thinking about the process of developing Shiny for Python. One, well, I'd say this

00:14:10.179 --> 00:14:15.460
isn't something I learned, but definitely some other people on the team learned. Jumping

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:21.619
to Python was not as scary as it sounded. I think for a lot of people that are on my team,

00:14:22.179 --> 00:14:27.299
R and JavaScript, but mostly R, was the language that they learned to program in and have invested

00:14:27.299 --> 00:14:34.659
many, many, many years of their lives and careers in. And there was a lot of assumption

00:14:35.219 --> 00:14:39.059
in the beginning that we are going to have to hire a bunch of Python experts.

00:14:43.619 --> 00:14:50.419
I don't want to oversimplify because I think it is not true that you can just pick up a book

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:57.219
and learn Python really well in just a few days. You really need to spend time with a language

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:02.580
to learn beyond just the syntax, learn the true Pythonic way to do things, and that takes some

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:06.659
time. But when you are working full-time on a project with a bunch of team members that are

00:15:06.659 --> 00:15:14.419
going through the same thing, it actually did not take very long for our devs to be quite productive

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:22.900
in Python. So that was one thing, is that on the technical side, it was not really a very

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:30.340
difficult transition for the team to become bilingual. And I think the second thing is that

00:15:31.299 --> 00:15:36.500
in Python, this might not be that interesting for data science, but for software engineering,

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:46.179
Python in recent versions has gotten better and better at static type-checking, so the ability

00:15:46.179 --> 00:15:53.140
to mark up your variables and function arguments with not only the name of a parameter, but the

00:15:53.140 --> 00:16:00.500
type that you expect it to be, and then having tools that will analyse your code and make sure

00:16:00.500 --> 00:16:05.380
that every function is being called in an appropriate way. Those tools, I think, are

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:10.419
mostly seen these days as a liability in data science, that they slow you down because you

00:16:10.419 --> 00:16:14.979
have to write this extra code. But when you are building something like Shiny, it's a huge help.

00:16:15.619 --> 00:16:21.299
And that's one of the things that I think coming away from shipping the first versions of Shiny

00:16:21.299 --> 00:16:24.580
for Python, it's like, it would have been really nice if we could have these same

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:32.820
tools on the R side to help us maintain Shiny for R. Sorry, can you remind me, what was the

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:39.059
second part of your question? Yeah, it's about feature parity. Do you see that as an asset or

00:16:39.059 --> 00:16:46.979
liability for your engineering team? Yeah, yeah. So do you mean feature parity between R and Python

00:16:46.979 --> 00:16:51.380
in general, or trying to achieve feature parity between Shiny for R and Shiny for Python?

00:16:51.380 --> 00:17:02.179
Shiny in specific. Oh, okay, yeah. So I think it is definitely a double-edged sword. It's

00:17:02.179 --> 00:17:09.060
super helpful to have built all this once before, because so many problems we not only have a

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:13.459
solution for, but we thought about multiple solutions before we decided on one. And we can

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:21.939
go back and reanalyze very quickly without having to invent too much stuff from whole cloth.

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:28.099
But the tough thing, I think, is that sometimes we are a little bit,

00:17:28.579 --> 00:17:33.619
we try not to, but we feel a little bit stuck with the decisions that we've made in the past.

00:17:33.619 --> 00:17:39.219
So the biggest one that we've been discussing to death, not, sorry, we've been discussing

00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:48.900
is Shiny modules is a feature for Shiny for R where if you want to, if your app is getting

00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:53.619
too complex, there's too much stuff going on in one server function or one UI, you can break it

00:17:53.619 --> 00:17:58.979
up into modules and those modules can be reused. They can be, they're namespaced. It really helps

00:17:58.979 --> 00:18:04.660
you reason about your app as a collection of smaller pieces. In Python, we have that feature

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:11.380
as well. It's also called Shiny modules. Well, Python modules are a thing in Python and the name

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:18.020
modules, like for us to move away from that for Python, it means now we have two. There are Shiny

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:24.739
modules for R and then there are Python components for Shiny for Python. And that is super annoying

00:18:24.739 --> 00:18:28.579
for all of us. So I think there are a lot of little things like this where we feel a little

00:18:28.579 --> 00:18:32.500
bit beholden to the past because it would be awkward to have different versions, but at the

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:38.099
same time, it doesn't necessarily always fit a hundred percent. It hasn't been that bad, but

00:18:38.099 --> 00:18:44.260
the times when it comes up, it is certainly as frustrating. Thank you. It's good perspective.

00:18:44.260 --> 00:18:50.020
Libby, I see you had a question in the chat. Do you want to jump in here?

00:18:52.099 --> 00:18:58.660
Sure. Can you hear me? My mic's been acting up. Sounds good. You can. Okay. Yeah. My question is

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:06.819
if you could go back in time to like 15 years ago, 20 years ago and tell yourself what you're doing

00:19:06.819 --> 00:19:10.420
right now, like what your career looks like, what your life looks like, what do you think would

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:24.739
surprise your younger self the most? Everything. Everything. I've been unbelievably fortunate

00:19:24.739 --> 00:19:32.819
in not only my career, but in my family life, in my relationship with my extended family. I mean,

00:19:33.459 --> 00:19:43.780
my life has, yeah, it's been an incredible run. And I think there were a set of things that I

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:51.300
really wanted to accomplish by the end of my career. And I don't know, I sort of find myself

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:58.579
in my mid forties, like needing to cast a new vision because all the things that I wanted to do,

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:04.579
I have just had the great privilege and been so fortunate as to have those things sort of

00:20:04.579 --> 00:20:11.939
happen to me in my career. And I think in particular, 15 years ago in my career, I felt like

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:22.260
I had stumbled into this incredible industry, just talking about tech in general, that back

00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:29.300
then had a very different feel, like it felt like we were, it was not quite as mainstream.

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:37.859
And I felt like I had stumbled into this, I mean, so fun, like such a fun way to make a living,

00:20:37.859 --> 00:20:46.819
to be writing programs all day with smart and interesting people. And to feel like I had

00:20:47.780 --> 00:20:53.780
like all my natural talents aligned with the skills and interests you need to be in software.

00:20:53.780 --> 00:21:02.020
And the thing that scared me 15 years ago was, what if all of my career contributions through

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:09.380
luck or happenstance add up to not very much? That was my fear, was that I have the education

00:21:09.380 --> 00:21:15.780
for this, I have the natural talent for this, I have the opportunity, but there's so much

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:19.939
luck involved, will I get the opportunity to actually do something that is interesting and

00:21:19.939 --> 00:21:29.459
meaningful? And when I was working on RStudio, I was already feeling like, oh, wow, this could

00:21:29.459 --> 00:21:36.660
really be it. And then Shiny felt like, okay, this is overdoing it a little bit. But I mean,

00:21:36.660 --> 00:21:44.819
it was like, I never had, I never pictured myself coming up with like a truly, I mean,

00:21:45.780 --> 00:21:51.459
I was going to say truly original idea. I mean, the idea is like 99% building on the shoulders of

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:57.699
reactive work that was done in JavaScript. But even like the insight to apply it in this new way

00:21:57.699 --> 00:22:05.780
on a server side to data science, I never aspired to have an idea like that. I just aspired for

00:22:05.780 --> 00:22:10.979
somebody else to have an idea and I would be able to help and for it to be like really impactful.

00:22:11.540 --> 00:22:18.099
So in our little corner of the world that is data science, Shiny has had a bigger impact than I was

00:22:18.099 --> 00:22:23.540
ever hoping for out of my career. So I think that would be the most comforting thing for me 15 years

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:29.459
