thank you, Joe. I see that there are a few questions earlier in the chat I want to get to.

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:10.500
But Dan, I see you, you put a question there about how you're starting to develop in Shiny

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.900
coming from Python. Do you want to jump in here with that?

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:18.660
Yeah, sure. Sure, Rachel. Hi, Joe. I am a, you know, more of a Python developer,

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:23.859
although I started years and years ago, many blue moons ago with R and really fell in love with it,

00:27:23.859 --> 00:27:29.300
and kind of coming back to it a little bit and trying to develop with Shiny. One frustration

00:27:29.300 --> 00:27:38.579
I have is just around debugging. And when you've got, you know, all these panes and windows and

00:27:38.660 --> 00:27:47.699
windows and UI widgets, can you share your thoughts around or best practices,

00:27:47.699 --> 00:27:53.619
tips, whatever, on the best way to kind of go through the debugging process?

00:27:54.579 --> 00:27:59.780
Yeah, absolutely. And can you just clarify, when you say debugging,

00:27:59.780 --> 00:28:03.859
you mean in a more general sense, not just using an interactive debugger?

00:28:04.339 --> 00:28:10.739
Yeah, correct. Like, I do everything in RStudio at the moment. And I run the app,

00:28:10.739 --> 00:28:16.819
all of a sudden, it just opens up and then closes. Or I run something, it spools an error.

00:28:17.380 --> 00:28:22.739
And, you know, it's not always obvious where the error actually is. It could be in the output side,

00:28:22.739 --> 00:28:28.339
it could be on the server side. And just maybe the pattern for debugging in

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:32.660
RShiny is just so different from what I'm used to. That could be it too.

00:28:32.819 --> 00:28:37.060
That could be it too. Yeah, it absolutely is. Well, especially if your work on Python,

00:28:37.060 --> 00:28:40.739
was it around, you know, like notebooks and scripts? Or were you...

00:28:41.300 --> 00:28:44.979
Yeah, you got it. Yeah. Jupyter notebooks, scripts, that kind of thing.

00:28:44.979 --> 00:28:49.939
Yeah, absolutely. So I think for those of you who did not use Shiny, especially,

00:28:51.540 --> 00:28:57.300
when you are doing sort of normal analysis with a notebook or a script on your desktop,

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:01.459
your code generally executes from beginning to end, right? Like you might have some functions,

00:29:01.459 --> 00:29:06.420
but those functions are called when you call them. And you have loops, but they loop when you loop.

00:29:07.219 --> 00:29:12.819
It's very transparent, like where the interpreter is at any given moment.

00:29:13.619 --> 00:29:21.380
With Shiny, and almost every other form of interactive framework, you provide

00:29:22.099 --> 00:29:28.660
code to the framework, and the framework decides when it executes. So it makes it much more,

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:35.859
much less intuitive to debug, because like, okay, this code is executing. Why is it executing? Like,

00:29:35.859 --> 00:29:43.219
how did it get here? There's much... It's much less transparent when code is executing,

00:29:43.219 --> 00:29:49.459
why it's executing. So there's a couple things that I'll tell you from a debugging perspective.

00:29:49.459 --> 00:29:55.619
Number one, I think that Hadley's book, Mastering Shiny, has a chapter on this. And we definitely

00:29:55.619 --> 00:29:59.859
have at least a couple of video resources where we've given talks about this. So I'd

00:29:59.859 --> 00:30:08.420
highly recommend those. But I have a couple of sort of principles that I always go back to as well.

00:30:09.699 --> 00:30:14.500
Number one, and maybe this less applies to you if you're coming from Python, but

00:30:15.699 --> 00:30:22.099
stack traces are very important. So when you... Often when you get an error in Shiny, you get a

00:30:22.979 --> 00:30:30.180
big bunch of lines spit out at the console that say, you know, from this file, this function name,

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:34.819
from this file, this function name, this file, this function name. And they often are like multiple

00:30:34.819 --> 00:30:39.939
lines. And often people find that scary, because a lot of the function names that are in there are

00:30:39.939 --> 00:30:43.619
function names that they might not recognize, because it's not code that they wrote that's

00:30:43.619 --> 00:30:47.780
executing. It's code that's inside of a package that's inside of a package that's, you know,

00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:57.060
calling base R, you know. Exactly, yeah. Yeah. So it's very important to not be afraid of that

00:30:57.060 --> 00:31:03.300
stack trace. It is very important to take the time to learn how to read those and understand

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:07.859
exactly what's going on. And what the stack trace is telling you is that at the moment that this

00:31:07.859 --> 00:31:14.500
error occurred, what were the functions in order that had been called? So if you think about,

00:31:14.500 --> 00:31:19.140
you know, at any given moment when code is executing for R, that code is probably in a

00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:23.939
function. And that function was called by another function. And that call was called by another

00:31:23.939 --> 00:31:27.780
function. And that call was... And so on and so forth. And it could be 20 levels deep.

00:31:27.780 --> 00:31:36.099
That is called your call stack. And when an error occurs, one of the most useful things to know is

00:31:36.099 --> 00:31:41.300
what was the call stack. And when that's printed to the console, now it's called a stack trace.

00:31:41.300 --> 00:31:46.099
So you can take that stack trace and you can read up it and just ignore the lines that you

00:31:46.099 --> 00:31:51.619
don't recognize and find the line that you do recognize that says this was the line of code

00:31:51.619 --> 00:31:57.939
in your app.R file. It was line 49. That was the thing that was executing when this error happened.

00:31:58.579 --> 00:32:04.020
And I think that, you know, for the easy cases where, let's say, I don't know, you

00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:13.380
use the wrong function name or you indexed into a data frame using an invalid variable or something

00:32:13.380 --> 00:32:19.939
like that, just understanding the stack trace, that will be enough for you to fix the problem.

00:32:19.939 --> 00:32:27.459
So that's one. The second thing you can do that's super useful is, especially in Shiny,

00:32:28.260 --> 00:32:33.780
never forget that there is a JavaScript console also that might be printing errors. And this is,

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:39.140
like, I feel really bad about this. We should do things in Shiny to surface this more prominently.

00:32:39.140 --> 00:32:43.859
But when you're in your browser looking at your Shiny app, if things are not behaving the way

00:32:43.859 --> 00:32:50.819
you expect and you don't see any errors in the R console, you can show the JavaScript console

00:32:50.819 --> 00:32:57.219
in your browser. And if you see a bunch of errors there, that's a big clue for you as well.

00:32:58.660 --> 00:33:01.619
Often that means there's some kind of bug in a component that you're using,

00:33:01.619 --> 00:33:07.380
whether it's in Shiny or some kind of third-party component. But, you know, if you're raising a

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:11.060
GitHub issue or whatever, that's some of the most useful information you can provide.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:17.699
The third, and I'll move on after this, is to so Shiny does demand that you write your code

00:33:17.699 --> 00:33:22.660
in a certain way. We have reactive outputs and reactive expressions, and you have to

00:33:22.660 --> 00:33:28.180
put your code in a certain place to get it to execute at the right time. That doesn't mean

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:34.020
that your sort of data science logic, that your data analysis, your data manipulation, and your

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:39.300
visualization, that logic doesn't have to live there. You can write functions that live off to

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:43.780
the side. They can even live in a separate function. They can even live in a package if you want.

00:33:43.780 --> 00:33:52.500
So you can write functions that are not Shiny. They're just R functions that perform the tasks

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:57.619
that you want, and you call them from Shiny. You call them from your Shiny outputs.

00:33:57.619 --> 00:34:01.859
The advantage of doing it this way is that if something goes wrong, you can test these pieces

00:34:01.859 --> 00:34:07.540
in isolation from the console. So you can make sure that each of these functions that you create,

00:34:07.540 --> 00:34:11.780
that do your data manipulation, that do your data visualization, you can ensure that they are

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:18.340
working correctly. And then your Shiny app collapses to just like a very small number of lines of code,

00:34:18.340 --> 00:34:22.899
and then it's much easier to reason about when things are being called and why.

00:34:22.899 --> 00:34:28.580
Yeah, that's helpful. I've been using the breakpoints and browser and things like that

00:34:29.620 --> 00:34:35.060
a little bit, but it's still, just compared to what I'm used to, a different mental model,

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:38.260
but I think what you laid out is helpful, so thank you.

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:43.939
Yeah, the browser and breakpoints are super helpful when you need them, but

00:34:44.500 --> 00:34:50.020
if you, like on my team, I'm constantly using the phrase, can you reason about it? I mean,

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:54.020
they must be so sick of me saying that, but like when you write code, it is not enough that it

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:57.300
works. If it's important for it to be right, it's not enough that it works. You have to be able to

00:34:57.300 --> 00:35:01.860
reason about it, and I find like browser is the most helpful when you have lost the ability to

00:35:01.860 --> 00:35:08.419
reason about your code. So definitely use it, but also think to yourself, like if this was really

00:35:08.419 --> 00:35:11.939
the only way for me to figure out what was going on, maybe it's time to refactor my code a little

00:35:12.500 --> 00:35:20.100
bit also. So, oh, great. Libby said, Libby Harin said, I love Tan Ho's little blurb,

00:35:20.100 --> 00:35:24.100
functions contain logic, modules call those functions, app bar calls the modules, that's

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:30.100
great. Yeah, there's a lot of great links and resources being shared in the chat too.

00:35:31.620 --> 00:35:36.260
Yeah, and just to remind everybody, you can save the chat too, so those little buttons below that

00:35:36.340 --> 00:35:44.820
say more, you could save those links there too. Joe, so another question, oh, Sam, I see you had

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:54.659
a question in the chat earlier. Do you want to jump in here? Yeah, sure. Yep. Okay, so I just

00:35:54.659 --> 00:35:59.699
had a question regarding the various development frameworks and what your thoughts are, development

00:36:00.179 --> 00:36:06.820
Golem, Rhino for production, great development. Has Pawset considered releasing their own framework

00:36:06.820 --> 00:36:14.100
once upon a time before their release? Yeah, the question is, if you guys are not familiar,

00:36:15.139 --> 00:36:22.580
there are a couple of packages that have been created to sort of provide more opinionated

00:36:22.580 --> 00:36:31.860
structure around how Shiny apps are written. So Golem and Rhino are probably the two, by far the

00:36:31.860 --> 00:36:40.260
two most popular. I have to say, I'm a little embarrassed, like this is a very important topic

00:36:40.260 --> 00:36:45.699
and I know people have like really strong opinions about this and in particular, I think Golem has

00:36:46.580 --> 00:36:54.580
huge proponents among people that I know and respect. I personally have not spent that much

00:36:54.580 --> 00:37:01.699
time with these frameworks. I think just the tradition that I come from in my background in

00:37:01.699 --> 00:37:13.540
software engineering, I feel like a lot of people, sorry, this is not the only reason people use

00:37:13.540 --> 00:37:18.899
these frameworks, but I do think that part of one thing that I've noticed that people really like

00:37:18.899 --> 00:37:24.419
in a lot of parts of data science is, especially if you didn't like set out to become a programmer,

00:37:24.419 --> 00:37:29.860
but accidentally became a programmer. I think a lot of people feel like if they're doing what it

00:37:29.860 --> 00:37:34.820
says in the tutorial, if they're doing what it says in an article that Hadley wrote, then they're

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:39.540
doing it right. And if they're doing something that they sort of invented or a pattern that they just

00:37:39.540 --> 00:37:46.179
came up with, then like that's a hack or that's a workaround or whatever. So I've had a lot of

00:37:46.179 --> 00:37:53.060
people ask me things, you know, like on the Shiny issues or Shiny forums and say like, hey, how do I

00:37:53.060 --> 00:37:59.219
solve this problem? Or it would be great if you had this feature. I solved it this way, but it would

00:37:59.219 --> 00:38:05.459
be nice to have it for real. And it's like, the way you did it is perfect. Like what about this

00:38:05.459 --> 00:38:10.979
solution does not satisfy you? And they're like, yeah, well, but I did it. So I would really like

00:38:10.979 --> 00:38:18.179
a grownup to do it, you know? And I think in the beginning, it felt like a lot of people were

00:38:18.179 --> 00:38:24.500
looking for a lot more guidance for how to structure their Shiny apps. And Gollum provided

00:38:25.540 --> 00:38:31.060
a set of opinions that people could look to, you know, Vincent and Colin and say, those people are

00:38:31.060 --> 00:38:37.780
clearly experts. If I use Gollum, then I'm like, I'm like allowed to do that. Whereas I had much

00:38:37.780 --> 00:38:43.939
more of an attitude of like, it's R, so you should feel free to package these things however you want.

00:38:43.939 --> 00:38:49.699
And you don't need anybody to tell you that that's, you know, okay or not. I do totally reserve the

00:38:49.699 --> 00:38:58.419
right to judge you, but you should do it anyway. So I think over the years, though, it has,

00:38:58.979 --> 00:39:03.699
like, more and more people have told me, like, this is, it is not just about that. It's not just

00:39:03.699 --> 00:39:09.459
like a set of opinions that are sort of nice to have that they actually do try to provide like a

00:39:10.979 --> 00:39:15.699
lower friction environment for you to do development and have been very thoughtful

00:39:15.699 --> 00:39:22.739
about how you sort of run and reload your app. And I totally believe that it has value. And I just,

00:39:22.739 --> 00:39:27.379
I have to admit, I have underinvested in spending time with those. But I certainly,

00:39:28.739 --> 00:39:34.659
you know, certainly I expect those things to work well, given how, you know, how much people use them.

00:39:38.419 --> 00:39:44.340
To go back to the question right before this, there was a follow-up question about,

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:48.580
like, could you say a little bit more about what you mean by can you reason about it?

00:39:49.540 --> 00:39:59.620
I think it might be helpful for us all. Yeah. It's my favorite topic. Yeah. So I think

00:40:02.340 --> 00:40:09.620
just to sort of reiterate, when you write software or do an analysis or whatever,

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:16.100
there's a level of I got it to work. And then there's the level of, like, it works and I can

00:40:16.179 --> 00:40:24.260
reason about it. And what that means is, like, software, complex pieces of software are among

00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:31.459
the most complicated thing, things that humankind has ever devised. You know, like, what other

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:38.179
human-made construct can have, you know, hundreds of millions of pieces and yet they're expected to

00:40:38.179 --> 00:40:47.139
all fit and work together so precisely that if one token is off, you know, rockets explode and,

00:40:47.699 --> 00:40:53.620
you know, you get the wrong answers. And I don't know what the limit is, but, like,

00:40:54.659 --> 00:40:59.540
you know, even the smartest humans, there is some small number of variables you can hold in your

00:40:59.540 --> 00:41:03.860
head. There's a small number of operations that you can hold in your head at any one time.

00:41:04.419 --> 00:41:13.219
So when we work on software that's non-trivial, when we work on software that in its totality

00:41:13.219 --> 00:41:17.699
is more than the human mind, more than any one human mind can hold at any one given time,

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:25.459
the main challenge in software engineering is about how do you take all this complexity and

00:41:25.459 --> 00:41:32.820
break it down into smaller pieces, each of which you can reason about, each of which you can hold

00:41:32.820 --> 00:41:43.780
in your head, each of which you can look at and be like, yeah, I can fully ingest this entire

00:41:43.780 --> 00:41:50.500
function definition. I can read it, you know, line by line and prove to myself this is definitely

00:41:50.500 --> 00:41:55.939
correct if the functions that it's calling don't have bugs and if it's called in the right way.

00:41:55.939 --> 00:41:59.860
So with those caveats, like, if the things that this thing is calling are correct

00:41:59.860 --> 00:42:05.060
and I'm called correctly, then the result will be correct because the logic here is correct.

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:13.620
So software engineering at all but the most beginner level is a lot about this. How do you

00:42:14.260 --> 00:42:20.340
break up inherently complicated things that we're trying to do into small pieces that are

00:42:20.899 --> 00:42:26.340
individually easy to reason about? And that's half the battle right there. The other half of the

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:34.979
battle is how do we combine them in ways that can be reliable and also easy to reason about?

00:42:34.979 --> 00:42:42.899
So it's these two pieces, small pieces reliably composed. If you can achieve that,

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:46.820
that's what I'm talking about. Like, that's software that you can reason about.

00:42:47.780 --> 00:42:56.899
So this has implications for data science as well, right? Like, when you have a data science,

00:42:57.860 --> 00:43:03.459
you're doing some kind of analysis on some data and it starts out as, oh, I'm just doing these

00:43:03.459 --> 00:43:08.659
simple things. I'm, like, doing this manipulation and then I'm doing this visualization. But then

00:43:08.659 --> 00:43:13.540
as you get deeper and deeper into it, it grows and grows and grows and grows. And you're at the point

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:18.419
where you're at the end and you don't remember where these variables came from. You don't

00:43:18.419 --> 00:43:23.939
remember, like, what's the difference between this data frame and this data frame. And you go back

00:43:23.939 --> 00:43:32.100
and hopefully start breaking it into functions. Or somehow dividing it into smaller pieces that

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:37.620
each focus on a thing and then you join those pieces together in your overall script. So that

00:43:37.939 --> 00:43:45.860
is, that's this principle of small pieces individually able to be reasoned about.

00:43:45.860 --> 00:43:49.780
And when you think about, like, other rules that you might have heard about software engineering,

00:43:49.780 --> 00:43:56.500
like, we know when you're writing functions, using global variables is bad. That's another one of

00:43:56.500 --> 00:44:01.219
these things where that hurts your ability to hold the entire function in your head and to prove that

00:44:01.780 --> 00:44:06.419
it'll work correctly because who knows who's setting that global variable to what value.

00:44:06.419 --> 00:44:13.060
So you can't prove to yourself, like, this function is definitely correct. So

00:44:15.540 --> 00:44:20.340
I think I, like, if there's anything that you're working on that needs to be correct,

00:44:21.379 --> 00:44:24.739
like, if you're just, like, zipping off some analysis and, like, it really doesn't matter,

00:44:24.739 --> 00:44:27.939
you just want a pretty picture or something like that, whatever. I don't know what that situation

00:44:27.939 --> 00:44:32.179
is. But if you don't care if the answer is right, sure. But if you do care that the answer is right,

00:44:32.179 --> 00:44:39.060
I try never to stop when I have an answer, but I can't reason about the code. I always try to go

00:44:39.060 --> 00:44:45.060
back and do the refactoring that's necessary just so I can prove to myself that the answer is right.

00:44:45.060 --> 00:44:49.379
Oh, and the other big benefit to this is that those individual pieces, if it does turn out

00:44:49.379 --> 00:44:54.500
that there's a mistake somewhere, you can individually debug, test, unit test those

00:44:54.500 --> 00:45:00.979
individual pieces. And when there are problems, you'll much more easily be able to find them.

