It is 1,000% different. It is completely and utterly different. And, I mean, it's hard to

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:14.899
enumerate how many differences that there are because there are so many. But the biggest by far

00:46:14.899 --> 00:46:24.820
is that, I mean, Python is just such a noisy space. Well, that's a really uncharitable word.

00:46:24.820 --> 00:46:35.300
It's a very vibrant and active space. I think in the early days of RStudio, the company,

00:46:38.580 --> 00:46:46.979
there was a lot of interest and activity around R. But it was not like Python is today. I mean,

00:46:46.979 --> 00:46:55.939
Python, just, you can't think of any niche and not find 15 packages that do that thing.

00:46:55.939 --> 00:47:00.100
And there are two more venture-backed ones coming out next week. I mean, it's just,

00:47:00.659 --> 00:47:10.820
the level of activity is on such a different level. And it's quite, it was quite a wake-up

00:47:10.820 --> 00:47:16.899
call to come into that. You know, going to conferences and things like that and realizing,

00:47:16.899 --> 00:47:24.659
like, okay, not only are we not a well-known entity in the Python world, especially after we

00:47:25.219 --> 00:47:32.179
rebranded the company, but, like, the amount that you would have to scream to get over this noise

00:47:32.739 --> 00:47:42.659
is just incredible. So, that was one big takeaway, is that we really don't have the luxury

00:47:42.659 --> 00:47:47.540
of being heard or taking for granted that we're going to be heard with any particular message

00:47:47.540 --> 00:47:53.060
that we have. And that makes it so much more important that when we tell our story,

00:47:53.060 --> 00:47:57.620
that we know exactly who we're telling it to and that we know exactly what's going to

00:47:57.620 --> 00:48:02.820
resonate with them. Because I think in the R community, when Shiny came out, people were

00:48:02.820 --> 00:48:06.659
willing to spend the time to find out, like, does this really make sense for me? And they were

00:48:06.659 --> 00:48:14.979
willing to do some work. And for Python, it's like, there's, like, 15 other options. So,

00:48:15.540 --> 00:48:23.060
like, why would you? And there are so many very, I think, because it's such a big community

00:48:23.620 --> 00:48:27.699
and there's so much, at least it's perceived that there's so much money to be made being

00:48:27.699 --> 00:48:32.500
content creators for this community or whatever other reasons people have for doing content

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:37.300
creation. I've heard that there is sort of like a content treadmill that people get on

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:41.540
that adds to the noise where it's like, you know, in order for the algorithm to take me seriously,

00:48:41.540 --> 00:48:49.300
I have to create a new, you know, Python package shootout every, you know, twice a week. And you

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:54.580
can only do so much research, you know, in three days. So, you end up with just this incredible

00:48:55.300 --> 00:49:00.340
volume of, like, very shallow noise. And that's just not something I ever remember

00:49:00.899 --> 00:49:08.260
being a big part of the R community. And I know it's, for Python users, it's both a blessing

00:49:08.260 --> 00:49:13.860
and a curse, right? Like, it's awesome to know that whatever it is that you want to solve,

00:49:13.860 --> 00:49:21.699
somebody is out there with either a free or paid solution for you. But now the work is figuring out

00:49:21.699 --> 00:49:26.580
which makes sense. And a lot of the analysis out there is not going to be too helpful.

00:49:28.179 --> 00:49:34.260
I will say, though, that in terms of the people that I've met in the community, there are, like,

00:49:34.260 --> 00:49:40.419
two really big takeaways that I have. Number one, that almost everybody that I've met has been

00:49:41.139 --> 00:49:50.659
very kind and generous to talk with us and, you know, pretty nice. And I don't know, like,

00:49:50.659 --> 00:49:56.260
I had heard people in the R community say, like, you know, I have been in the Python community,

00:49:56.260 --> 00:50:02.659
and boy, it's so refreshing to be here and whatever. And at least the particular conferences

00:50:02.659 --> 00:50:08.580
that I've been to, and, you know, being 2022, 2023, I don't know how it was, you know, 10 years ago.

00:50:08.580 --> 00:50:15.060
But, yeah, I really saw a lot of the same things that I like in the R community happening in the

00:50:15.060 --> 00:50:22.419
Python community, maybe without the sort of slightly more tightly knit feeling that comes from,

00:50:23.699 --> 00:50:28.899
you know, being a smaller community for so many years. But the other thing is that it's such a

00:50:28.899 --> 00:50:35.139
big community that I feel like it is very, very hard to generalize what people, like, what a

00:50:35.139 --> 00:50:42.739
Python data scientist even is. It is hard to even divide it into four or five groups. There are just,

00:50:42.739 --> 00:50:49.459
there's so much diversity. There are people who are, like, so much more commercial than the average

00:50:49.459 --> 00:50:57.620
R user is, who are so much more focused on, like, you know, this is a purely commercial sort of

00:50:57.620 --> 00:51:05.780
interest for them, to people who are so much more extreme free software zealots than I have ever met.

00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:10.179
And that's coming from someone who obviously, like, really, really believes in open source software.

00:51:10.179 --> 00:51:15.620
I had, like, a couple people ask us at PyData Seattle, okay, so, like, you have all this open

00:51:15.620 --> 00:51:23.300
source stuff, but you also have, like, these complimentary, you know, commercial offerings.

00:51:24.260 --> 00:51:30.100
Like, to me, you don't count as open source. It's like, what? Or people who say, like,

00:51:31.060 --> 00:51:37.139
because your governance model is not open and you don't have, like, a democratically elected board,

00:51:37.139 --> 00:51:45.379
you're not open source. I'm like, like, cool that you have that position. Totally respect that. But

00:51:45.379 --> 00:51:50.179
to say that open source is the word that means the thing that I like, I'm like, wow, this is not

00:51:50.179 --> 00:51:55.939
something that I have ever encountered in the R world. So, again, the whole spectrum has been

00:51:55.939 --> 00:52:00.500
represented at each of the conferences I've been to. And I was, I guess I was a little bit surprised

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:05.139
that it's not just, like, such a big community, but so incredibly, incredibly, incredibly diverse.

00:52:08.739 --> 00:52:13.379
Awesome. Thank you. I appreciate hearing all of that so much. Really, really grateful for your

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:19.620
thoughts on that. Thanks, Joe. Thanks, Joe. I see there was an anonymous question from

00:52:20.340 --> 00:52:23.620
actually towards the beginning, I want to make sure I get to as well. And it was,

00:52:24.899 --> 00:52:31.300
I get questions from IT and leadership about data security with Shiny apps. What training or tools

00:52:31.300 --> 00:52:39.219
do you recommend for testing our Shiny apps? For example, like pen test? Yeah, that is a really

00:52:39.219 --> 00:52:44.899
good question. I used to have good answers for this because we would receive the pen test reports

00:52:44.899 --> 00:52:55.780
from people. And I will say two things about those pen tests, I think. One, I was surprised

00:52:56.500 --> 00:53:04.979
how well those pen test tools worked against Shiny in the sense that, like, the tools didn't break,

00:53:04.979 --> 00:53:09.139
like they did actually run their tests and treat Shiny as no different than any other web app that

00:53:09.139 --> 00:53:15.060
they would test. So that was cool to see. And there were, you know, results that, like,

00:53:15.060 --> 00:53:23.219
once in a blue moon would actually be relevant. But on the other hand, I think, like, in my

00:53:23.219 --> 00:53:31.300
experience, the false positive ratio to, you know, true security issue, that ratio is, like,

00:53:31.300 --> 00:53:37.699
it's really surprisingly noisy. And, like, noisy in a scary way, because,

00:53:39.540 --> 00:53:43.219
like, they sound very, very plausible. Like, these reports come back and they sound very,

00:53:43.219 --> 00:53:49.540
very plausible. But, like, nine times out of 10, they're just using heuristics and don't

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:53.860
really understand, like, what the parameters they are looking at and what value they have.

00:53:54.419 --> 00:53:59.860
So I would say if your organization says to use them, I would expect whatever pen test,

00:54:00.739 --> 00:54:09.060
whatever web-based pen test tool that you're using to work. But if you have red flags come up,

00:54:09.060 --> 00:54:15.300
expect to have to go through our support and talk it through with them. In terms of actually

00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:22.899
improving your security, I think a higher value thing is to read the, there's a very standard,

00:54:22.899 --> 00:54:29.300
I think OWASP is the acronym, O-W-A-S-P, the Open Web Application Security Project or something

00:54:29.300 --> 00:54:35.379
like that. And they have an ever-evolving list of, like, the top ten vulnerabilities,

00:54:35.379 --> 00:54:40.580
classes of vulnerabilities you need to worry about when you're building your web applications.

00:54:40.580 --> 00:54:47.139
And I found those to be consistently excellent advice. Like, every one of those vulnerabilities

00:54:47.699 --> 00:54:54.179
is one you should at least be aware of. And if you're a more experienced Shiny developer,

00:54:54.179 --> 00:55:00.260
hopefully you should be able to at least be able to connect the dots between how they're

00:55:00.260 --> 00:55:05.780
expressing the problem and how that might affect your Shiny app. Like, you know, code injection

00:55:05.780 --> 00:55:10.260
is one example where you take a parameter from a user, and the classic one is you just take

00:55:10.260 --> 00:55:15.620
whatever name they typed in and you just, like, glom that onto the end of a SQL query string that

00:55:15.620 --> 00:55:22.020
you have, right, and put, like, quotes around it. But that's, that user, that input is coming from

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:29.939
the user. They could put, you know, a single quote in their input, and that would finish your

00:55:29.939 --> 00:55:37.379
string, and now their input is being interpreted as SQL code. There's a famous XKCD about this. If

00:55:37.379 --> 00:55:46.419
you Google for Bobby Tables, you'll find it. So that's an example of, like, a SQL injection.

00:55:46.419 --> 00:55:50.419
That's totally something that if you weren't paying attention, you could introduce into a

00:55:50.419 --> 00:55:56.500
Shiny app, right? You could form a SQL query that you're about to send to, you know, Oracle or

00:55:56.500 --> 00:56:01.860
Postgres and add user input to the end. So there are things that you need to do to not do that.

00:56:01.860 --> 00:56:08.100
So for sure, run the pen test if your organization does that. But I think more important, read

00:56:08.100 --> 00:56:13.459
through the OWASP list of vulnerabilities.

